headline.main: Breakaway Space Satellite Finally Dies Out

results.snippet: The runaway satellite-on-a-rope fell silent and became just another piece of  space junk today when its batteries finally died, five days after it had broken  away from the shuttle Columbia.         The Italian-made satellite and its American-made...
results.lead_paragraph: The runaway satellite-on-a-rope fell silent and became just another piece of space junk today when its batteries finally died, five days after it had broken away from the shuttle Columbia. The Italian-made satellite and its American-made tether to the shuttle generated electricity for several hours last Sunday, and delivered that electricity to the shuttle, as they swept through Earth's magnetic field. But the experiment soon went awry, as the cable snapped even before being extended from the shuttle to its full length of nearly 13 miles. The satellite, with 12 miles of cable attached, has been floating free ever since.

headline.main: A Composer Who Finds Lasting Inspiration in 'Alice in Wonderland'

results.snippet: IN a small cottage in Sag Harbor's North Haven, David Del Tredici sits playing the piano as he meets the man who has come to take his picture. He is playing with just one hand -- almost unconsciously, with a feeling of both anxiety and release -- as...
results.lead_paragraph: IN a small cottage in Sag Harbor's North Haven, David Del Tredici sits playing the piano as he meets the man who has come to take his picture. He is playing with just one hand -- almost unconsciously, with a feeling of both anxiety and release -- as he turns to pose. Behind the Pulitzer Prize-winning composer, who for more than 20 years has set bits of the text of "Alice in Wonderland" to music, there is a poster-sized photograph of himself as a very small boy on a tricycle, as if already posing before some unseen audience.

results.lead_paragraph: At first, all sides proclaimed victory in the Battle of the Guadalcanal, the fight that ended with the city agreeing to change course and abandon its plan to anchor the aircraft carrier Guadalcanal next to the Intrepid Sea-Air-Space Museum in the Hudson River and use it as a heliport, mainly for sightseeing flights. Plans now call for the heliport to be built a half-mile south, on the site of the city's towed-car pound opposite the Jacob K. Javits Convention Center, and to be run by the museum. The Guadalcanal will remain berthed in the Delaware River, at the Philadelphia Navy Yard.

results.lead_paragraph: Lieut. Yuri A. Gagarin, the Soviet astronaut who, on April 12, 1961, was the first human in space, did not have the seamless triumph that Moscow publicized for so many decades. In fact, man's first voyage beyond the planet was nearly a disaster. Memorabilia from the Soviet space program to be auctioned this month at Sotheby's include documents that show that lieutenant Gagarin had a close brush with death aboard Vostok 1.

headline.main: Russian Space Mementos Show Gagarin's Ride was a Rough One

results.snippet: THE launching of the first human into space by the Soviet Union -- a 108-minute dash around the globe by Lieut. Yuri A. Gagarin on April 12, 1961 --  stunned the world, particularly the United States, which at the time was struggling to catch up in...
results.lead_paragraph: THE launching of the first human into space by the Soviet Union -- a 108-minute dash around the globe by Lieut. Yuri A. Gagarin on April 12, 1961 -- stunned the world, particularly the United States, which at the time was struggling to catch up in the space race. Shortly after the Soviet success, President Kennedy, under enormous pressure to outdo the Communists, announced a bold plan to land Americans on the Moon by the end of the decade. But it turns out that Lieutenant Gagarin's flight aboard Vostok 1 was far from the seamless triumph that Moscow publicized for so many decades. In fact, man's first voyage beyond the planet was nearly a disaster, Western aerospace experts have learned.

results.lead_paragraph: When Patrick Ewing trotted onto the Spectrum floor in Philadelphia last night, his undistinguished teammates included Brad Lohaus and J. R. Reid, and his coach was a career assistant named Jeff Van Gundy. The names might as well have been Ken Bannister, Eddie Lee Wilkins and Bob Hill. Ewing was suddenly all the way back to 1986, when the Knicks fired Hubie Brown and Ewing floated in limbo, like an astronaut gripping a lifeline in space. Now he is again part of a team with no contender's nucleus, no real coach, no identity, no guaranteed plan. He is no closer to a championship, only a decade older.

headline.main: If Wind Eases, Space Shuttle Will Revisit The Russians

results.snippet: For the third time in less than a year, the space shuttle Atlantis is set for launching toward a linkup with the Russian space station Mir, another rehearsal  for the assembly and operation of an international space station later in the decade.      ...
results.lead_paragraph: For the third time in less than a year, the space shuttle Atlantis is set for launching toward a linkup with the Russian space station Mir, another rehearsal for the assembly and operation of an international space station later in the decade. But this is the first time the shuttle is to leave behind an American astronaut. That astronaut, Dr. Shannon Lucid, is to live on Mir for nearly five months. She is to be followed on Mir by at least four other Americans on a rotating basis through the spring of 1998.

headline.main: Shuttle Blasts Off, but Hydraulic Leak May Curtail Flight

results.snippet: With an explosion of daylight in the dark of night, the space shuttle Atlantis rocketed into orbit early today on a flight to link up with the Russian space station Mir, the third such mission in less than a year.         But a leaky power unit in...
results.lead_paragraph: With an explosion of daylight in the dark of night, the space shuttle Atlantis rocketed into orbit early today on a flight to link up with the Russian space station Mir, the third such mission in less than a year. But a leaky power unit in the shuttle's steering system raised concerns that the mission might not be able to run its full nine days. Space agency officials emphasized that the malfunction was not life-threatening. Only one of the three identical hydraulic systems, which are used to control wing flaps, the rudder and landing gear, is malfunctioning. The leak, moreover, has apparently been halted at least for the time being, but could recur when the system is switched back on for the shuttle's descent and landing.

headline.main: Astronauts Haul Supplies to Space Station

results.snippet: Working like skycaps high above Earth, American and Russian astronauts lugged 12-gallon sacks of water and other supplies today from the space shuttle Atlantis to the Russian space station Mir.         An American astronaut, Dr. Shannon Lucid, was...
results.lead_paragraph: Working like skycaps high above Earth, American and Russian astronauts lugged 12-gallon sacks of water and other supplies today from the space shuttle Atlantis to the Russian space station Mir. An American astronaut, Dr. Shannon Lucid, was excused from most of the heavy lifting. Assigned to the station for the next five months, she spent her second day as a Mir crew member settling in and reacquainting herself with her Russian colleagues, Yuri Onufrienko and Yuri Usachev.

results.lead_paragraph: Two space-walking astronauts hung the orbital equivalent of flypaper on the Russian space station Mir today to collect cosmic grit. "It doesn't get any better," said one astronaut, Dr. Linda Godwin, a physicist aboard the space shuttle Atlantis. The shuttle and the Mir are docked in orbit more than 250 miles above Earth.
